	</ul>
	<div class="ibox-image"><a href="./File:Chinese-grammar-wiki-zhe.jpg" class="image"><img alt="Chinese-grammar-wiki-zhe.jpg" src="https://resources.allsetlearning.com/gramwiki/images/thumb/2/2e/Chinese-grammar-wiki-zhe.jpg/300px-Chinese-grammar-wiki-zhe.jpg" decoding="async" width="300" height="300" srcset="https://resources.allsetlearning.com/gramwiki/images/thumb/2/2e/Chinese-grammar-wiki-zhe.jpg/450px-Chinese-grammar-wiki-zhe.jpg 1.5x, https://resources.allsetlearning.com/gramwiki/images/thumb/2/2e/Chinese-grammar-wiki-zhe.jpg/600px-Chinese-grammar-wiki-zhe.jpg 2x" /></a></div>
</div> 
<p>The particle 着 (zhe) is one way of indicating the <i>continuous aspect</i> in Mandarin Chinese (another common way is <a href="Expressing_actions_in_progress" class="mw-redirect" title="Expressing actions in progress">using the adverb 在 in front of verbs</a>).  You may have heard that the Chinese particle 着 added onto the end of verbs is similar to the use of <i>-ing</i> in English.  This isn't particularly helpful, however, because the use of 着 in Chinese is not nearly so commonly used, and can also be quite idiomatic.
</p>
<div id="toc" class="toc"><input type="checkbox" role="button" id="toctogglecheckbox" class="toctogglecheckbox" style="display:none" /><div class="toctitle" lang="en" dir="ltr"><h2>Contents</h2><span class="toctogglespan"><label class="toctogglelabel" for="toctogglecheckbox"></label></span></div>
<ul>
